{"title_page": "Jamie Maclaren", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Jamie Maclaren\n| image = Jamie Maclaren World Cup 2018.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Maclaren at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] with [[Socceroos|Australia]]\n| fullname = Jamie Maclaren<ref name=\"FIFA\">{{cite web |title=FIFA Confederations Cup Russia 2017: List of players: Australia |url=http://tournament.fifadata.com/documents/FCC/2017/PDF/FCC_2017_SQUADLISTS.PDF |publisher=FIFA |format=PDF |page=1 |date=2 July 2017 |accessdate=21 July 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724170755/http://tournament.fifadata.com/documents/FCC/2017/PDF/FCC_2017_SQUADLISTS.PDF |archivedate=24 July 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|07|29|df=yes}}<ref name=\"Football Federation Australia\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.perthglory.com.au/player/jamie-maclaren/9kdku1z6yggd1eeiz03jq5mlp |title=Team \u2013 Jamie Maclaren |work=Perth Glory FC Site |publisher=Football Federation Australia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510231729/http://www.perthglory.com.au/player/jamie-maclaren/9kdku1z6yggd1eeiz03jq5mlp |archive-date=10 May 2015 |access-date=8 May 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Sunbury, Victoria|Sunbury]], Australia<ref name=\"Football Federation Australia\" />\n| height = 1.79 m<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamie Maclaren |url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/jamie-maclaren/299758/ |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n| currentclub = [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]]\n| clubnumber = 9\n| youthyears1 = 1998\u20132003\n| youthclubs1 = Sunbury United\n| youthyears2 = 2003\u20132009\n| youthclubs2 = [[Green Gully SC|Green Gully]]\n| youthyears3 = 2009\u20132013\n| youthclubs3 = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]\n| years1 = 2013\u20132015\n| caps1 = 38\n| goals1 = 11\n| clubs1 = [[Perth Glory FC|Perth Glory]]\n| years2 = 2014\u20132015\n| caps2 = 5\n| goals2 = 11\n| clubs2 = [[Perth Glory FC Reserves|Perth Glory NPL]]\n| years3 = 2015\u20132017\n| caps3 = 53\n| goals3 = 40\n| clubs3 = [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]]\n| years4 = 2017\u20132019\n| caps4 = 7\n| goals4 = 0\n| clubs4 = [[SV Darmstadt 98]]\n| years5 = 2018\u20132019\n| caps5 = 27\n| goals5 = 9\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] (loan)\n| years6 = 2019\u2013\n| caps6 = 29\n| goals6 = 23\n| clubs6 = [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]]\n| club-update = 23:11, 23 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalyears1 = 2011\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2012\u20132013\n| nationalteam2 = [[Australia national under-20 soccer team|Australia U20]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 17\n| nationalgoals2 = 9\n| nationalyears3 = 2014\u20132016\n| nationalteam3 = [[Australia national under-23 soccer team|Australia U23]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 15\n| nationalgoals3 = 9\n| nationalyears4 = 2016\u2013\n| nationalteam4 = [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 15\n| nationalgoals4 = 5\n| nationalteam-update = 15:09, 15 October 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Jamie Maclaren''' (born 29 July 1993) is an Australian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]]. He has also previously played for [[SV Darmstadt 98]], [[Perth Glory FC]], [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]] and [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]]. Maclaren initially represented Scotland at youth level, but has since appeared for [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]] at both youth and senior international level. He won the 2016\u201317 A-League Golden Boot with 19 goals.\n\n==Club career==\n===Early years===\nJamie Maclaren grew up in the north-western suburbs of [[Melbourne]]. He first joined the junior side of local team Sunbury United at the early age of four or five, then switched to the youth ranks of nearby Victorian Premier League (now [[National Premier Leagues Victoria]]) side [[Green Gully SC|Green Gully]] in 2003, where although he continued to play against older players, his team was very successful, at one point winning around 50 games in a row.\n\n===Blackburn Rovers===\nIn July 2009, aged 15, he was invited to trial for [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers']] under-16 squad. In his first trial match he scored two goals against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]'s under-16 squad, followed by a [[hat-trick]] against [[Manchester United]], which resulted in a contract offer from Rovers.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.goalweekly.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1052:maclaren-raves-about-rovers&catid=42:football-focus&Itemid=66 |title=Young Victorian Signs for Blackburn Rovers |date=16 June 2010 |work=Goal Weekly}}</ref>\n\nMaclaren benefited from the mentorship of fellow Australians [[Vince Grella]] and [[Brett Emerton]] at Blackburn, where he soon progressed to be a regular under-21 squad player and training with the senior team.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.blackburn.vitalfootball.co.uk/sitepage.asp?a=295076 |title=Getting to Know....Jamie Maclaren! |date=1 October 2012 |work=Vital Football |access-date=9 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625074006/http://www.blackburn.vitalfootball.co.uk/sitepage.asp?a=295076 |archive-date=25 June 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, after four years in England having not broken into the first team, he was released by Rovers at the end of the 2012\u201313 season.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/sport/10461885._/ |title=Blackburn Rovers confirm released list |date=4 June 2013 |work=Lancashire Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n===Perth Glory===\nSeeking first-team game time, Maclaren elected to return to Australia and signed a three-year contract with [[A-League]] club [[Perth Glory]] at the beginning of the 2013\u201314 season.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/sport/a/17831735/glory-sign-young-gun-maclaren/  |title=Glory sign young gun Maclaren |last=Hope |first=Shayne |date=2 July 2013 |work=The West Australian}}</ref> Maclaren made his Perth Glory debut, where he played 90 minutes, in a 3\u20131 loss against [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-10-13/roar-steal-win-over-phoenix/5019304 |title=Adelaide United cops two red cards in win over Perth Glory; Roar nicks it in injury time against Phoenix |date=13 October 2013 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |access-date=21 July 2016}}</ref> Maclaren then scored his first goal for Perth Glory weeks later, on 27 October 2013, in a 1\u20130 win over [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Perth Glory edges Melbourne Heart thanks to Jamie Maclaren goal, Wellington Phoenix and Newcastle Jets scoreless|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-10-27/phoenix-and-jets-produce-napier-stalemate/5048500|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=27 October 2013|accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> and scored his second Perth Glory goal on 23 November 2013<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-11-24/mariners-grab-key-away-win-over-perth/5113170 |title=Central Coast Mariners clinch 2\u20131 victory over Perth Glory with 94th minute winner by Mitch Duke |date=23 November 2013 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |access-date=21 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe 2014\u201315 season was his breakout year, scoring 10 goals in 23 appearances across all competitions, and earning the April nomination for the league's young player of the year award.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/article/nab-young-footballer-of-the-year-nominee-for-april/cnvxrq1w5ut2177rps1vpz1wk#xk04dTURicq9qJjs.99 |title=NAB Young Footballer of the Year nominee for April |date=30 April 2015 |publisher=Football Federation Australia}}</ref> He also made a number of appearances in the [[National Premier Leagues]] side scoring 11 goals in just five games.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.perthglory.com.au/article/glory-end-the-npl-wa-season-in-style/1sq5uuxun742x1w6j144vb31dn |title=Glory end the NPL-WA season in style |date=25 August 2014 |publisher=Perth Glory FC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.perthglory.com.au/article/5-star-glory-salute-floreat/1c1nugs32zm1t1tpwmsgko3u7o |title=5-star Glory salute Floreat |date=26 April 2014 |publisher=Perth Glory FC}}</ref> Maclaren scored his first senior club hat-trick, scoring all three of Glory's goals in a 3\u20131 win against Melbourne City on 19 April 2015.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-04-19/perth-glory-beats-melbourne-city-thanks-to-maclaren-hat-trick/6404470 |title=Perth Glory beats Melbourne City thanks to MacLaren hat-trick |date=19 April 2015 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 2014\u201315 season, in the fallout from the [[2014\u201315 A-League#League table|Perth Glory salary cap scandal]], Glory agreed to release all contracted players who wished to leave the club, with the sole exception of Maclaren. In response, he lodged a formal breach-of-contract notice against Perth Glory to the players' Union, [[Professional Footballers Australia]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/football/jamie-maclaren-in-contract-impasse-with-perth-glory/story-fni2fq7p-1227376203082 |title=Jamie Maclaren in contract impasse with Perth Glory |last=Davutovic |first=David |date=30 May 2015 |work=Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/sport/a/27990119/maclaren-in-legal-bid-to-quit-glory/  |title=Maclaren in legal bid to quit Glory |last=Miller |first=Dale |date=16 May 2015 |work=The West Australian}}</ref> Maclaren was subsequently released by Glory on 29 June 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.perthglory.com.au/article/perth-glory-releases-jamie-maclaren/s188be97grig1m8xq9vawtojm|publisher=[[Perth Glory FC|Perth Glory]]|title=Perth Glory releases Jamie Maclaren|date=29 June 2015|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Brisbane Roar===\n[[File:Jamie Maclaren Brisbane Liverpool July 2015.jpg|left|thumb|Maclaren playing with the [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]] in 2015]]\nDuring the A-League off-season, on 5 July 2015, [[Brisbane Roar]] signed Maclaren to a two-year deal.<ref>{{cite news|last=Monteverde|first=Marco|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/football/a-league-brisbane-roar-sign-former-perth-glory-striker-jamie-maclaren-on-a-two-year-deal/story-fnk6pqhe-1227429553522|title=A-League: Brisbane Roar sign former Perth Glory striker Jamie Maclaren on a two-year deal|work=The Courier-Mail|publisher=News Corp|date=5 July 2015|accessdate=5 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nMaclaren made his debut with the Roar against the [[Western Sydney Wanderers FC|Western Sydney Wanderers]] on 8 October 2015. In the same game, he scored a brace for the Roar, with goals in the 9th and 34th minutes of the match.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.a-league.com.au/matchcentre/Western-Sydney-Wanderers-FC-v-Brisbane-Roar-FC/811609?matchstats#widget-match-day-tabs |title=Roar shock Wanderers in season opener |date=8 October 2015 |publisher=A League Official Website}}</ref> Later that season Maclaren reached his 50th senior A-League appearance, scoring a goal and assisting another against his former club, Perth Glory. He scored his second senior club hat-trick in a win against [[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]] on 12 March 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-03-12/mclaren-hat-trick-sends-roar-top-with-5-0-win-over-victory/7242506 |title=Jamie Maclaren triple sends Brisbane Roar top with 5\u20130 win over Melbourne Victory |date=12 March 2016 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>\n\nMaclaren finished the A-League regular season with 18 goals, second in the Golden Boot race to [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City's]] [[Uruguayan]] striker [[Bruno Fornaroli]], however his season tally was enough to become the all-time A-League record for an Australian player. Maclaren scored two more goals in the finals series to make his final club goal count 20 from 25 games. At the end of the 2015\u201316 season, he was awarded as the Young Player of the Year by the FFA.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.a-league.com.au/article/brisbane-roars-jamie-maclaren-named-nab-young-footballer-of-the-year/zbvcqzhbqyjv17zsavx62kbkf |title=Maclaren named NAB Young Footballer of the Year |date=26 April 2016 |publisher=Football Federation Australia}}</ref>\n\nMaclaren scored 19 goals for the Roar in the [[2016-17 A-League]] regular season, tying with [[Besart Berisha]] for the Golden Boot.<ref>[http://www.fourfourtwo.com.au/news/maclaren-berisha-share-golden-boot-honours-458510 Maclaren, Berisha Share Golden Boot Honours] FourFourTwo Australia, 16 April 2017</ref>\n\n===SV Darmstadt 98===\nIn May 2017, Maclaren joined German [[2. Bundesliga]] club [[SV Darmstadt 98|Darmstadt 98]] signing a three-year deal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jamie Maclaren signs for SV Darmstadt|url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2017/05/19/jamie-maclaren-signs-sv-darmstadt-0|accessdate=19 May 2017|work=[[Special Broadcasting Service]]|date=19 May 2017}}</ref> He made his debut in the second round of the season as a 63rd minute substitution in a 1\u20131 draw away to [[1. FC Kaiserslautern|FC Kaiserslautern]] on 4 August.<ref>[http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/2bundesliga/startseite/2-bundesliga/2017-18/2/3827899/spielbericht_1-fc-kaiserslautern-37_sv-darmstadt-98-98.html Match Report], [[Kicker (sports magazine)|Kicker]], 4 August 2017</ref>\n\n====Loans to Hibernian====\nMaclaren was loaned to Scottish club [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] in January 2018, in the hope that more playing time would boost his chances of being selected by Australia for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/football/socceroos-transfer-news-jamie-maclaren-signs-for-hibernian-on-loan/news-story/9d83ddda874314ce34d221de392e8db4|title=Socceroos transfer news: Jamie Maclaren signs for Hibernian on loan|newspaper=[[news.com.au]]|date=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hibernianfc.co.uk/news/8299 |title=Maclaren Signs for Hibernian |publisher=Hibernian FC |work= |date=8 January 2018 |accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> He made his [[Scottish Premiership]] debut in a 1\u20130 win at [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]] on 24 January.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42713341 |title=Dundee v Hibernian |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 January 2018 |accessdate=}}</ref> Maclaren scored his first goal for Hibs on 3 February, converting a match-winning [[penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42933674 |title=Rangers 1\u20132 Hibernian: victory 'up there' with beating Barca \u2013 Neil Lennon |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 February 2018 |accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref> He scored the second goal in a 2\u20130 win for Hibs in an [[Edinburgh derby]] on 9 March,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43251605 |title=Hibernian 2\u20130 Heart of Midlothian |first=Brian |last=McLauchlin |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date= 9 March 2018 |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> and helped to delay [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic's]] title celebrations by scoring the first goal in a 2\u20131 win for Hibs on 21 April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43762819 |title=Hibernian 2\u20131 Celtic |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 April 2018 |accessdate=}}</ref> He ended his season in Scotland by scoring a [[list of Scottish Professional Football League hat-tricks|hat-trick]] in a 5\u20135 draw with Rangers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44020118 |title=Hibernian 5\u20135 Rangers |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |first=Brian |last=McLauchlin |date=13 May 2018 |accessdate=13 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the loan spell ended, Maclaren said that he hoped Darmstadt would make him available for transfer.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hibs/jamie-maclaren-fears-he-could-be-priced-out-of-return-to-hibs-1-4739264 |title=Jamie Maclaren fears he could be priced out of return to Hibs |first=David |last=Hardie |work=Edinburgh Evening News |publisher= |date=15 May 2018 |accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref> On 3 August, Maclaren returned to Hibernian on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45063174 |title=Hibernian announce loan deal for striker Jamie Maclaren |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 August 2018 |accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref> This spell was less productive, as Maclaren only scored one goal and he struggled to hold down a regular place in the starting lineup.<ref name = \"loan term\"/> Hibs terminated the loan on 31 January 2019.<ref name = \"loan term\">{{cite news |url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hibs/jamie-maclaren-leaves-hibs-after-club-terminates-loan-1-4865767 |title=Jamie Maclaren leaves Hibs after club terminates loan |first=Mark |last=Atkinson |date=31 January 2019 |accessdate=31 January 2019 |work=Edinburgh Evening News}}</ref>\n\n===Melbourne City===\n[[File:Jamie Maclaren Goal.jpg|thumb|Jamie Maclaren scores against Melbourne Victory 07.02.20 ]]\nOn the 31st of January 2019 Maclaren signed for [[A-League]] club [[Melbourne City FC]] on a marquee deal to see him at the club till May 2022. He scored in his first game for City with a backheel against [[Adelaide United]] on 9 February.\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Jamie Maclaren training with the Socceroos June 2017.jpg|thumb|right|Maclaren training with the Socceroos in 2017]]\nHis international career started when he was called up for [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland under-19]], who he was eligible to play for through his father Donald. Maclaren made two appearances for the team, playing against Denmark and Norway. Maclaren was then involved with the [[Australia national under-20 association football team|Australian under-20]] squad, and scored a goal against the hosts Turkey in the [[2013 FIFA U-20 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rovers.co.uk/news/article/country-calls-for-duo-376600.aspx|title=Country calls for duo|publisher=Blackburn Rovers F.C.|date=19 September 2012|accessdate=21 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721223621/http://www.rovers.co.uk/news/article/country-calls-for-duo-376600.aspx|archivedate=21 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMaclaren joined the [[Australia national under-23 soccer team|Australian under-23 team]] (\"Olyroos\") for [[2016 AFC U-23 Championship qualification]] Group F games held in [[Taiwan]] in March 2015, which doubled as Olympic qualification. He played in two of the Olyroos' three games, scoring a hat-trick against [[Hong Kong national under-23 football team|Hong Kong]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.the-afc.com/afcasfeeds?fixtureid=8831&stageid=348&tMode=H&view=ajax&show=matchsummary |title=Australia 6\u20130 Hong Kong \u2013 Match Summary |publisher=The Asian Football Confederation}}</ref> and another two goals against [[Myanmar national under-23 football team|Myanmar]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.the-afc.com/afcasfeeds?fixtureid=8835&stageid=348&tMode=H&view=ajax&show=matchsummary |title=Australia 5\u20131 Myanmar \u2013 Match Summary |publisher=The Asian Football Confederation}}</ref> achieving the second highest tally for the qualification stage out of the entire [[Asian Football Confederation|AFC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-afc.com/afcasfeeds?&view=ajax&show=mod_topScorer&stageid=348&disp=all|title=Top Goal Scorers (by Stage) \u2013 2016 AFC U-23 Championship Qualifiers|publisher=AFC.com}}</ref> Maclaren was named in the Australian squad for the [[2016 AFC U-23 Championship]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/football/socceroos/olyroos-squad-aurelio-vidmar-confirms-squad-for-afc-under-23s-championship/story-e6frf4l3-1227687022607 |title=Olyroos squad: Aurelio Vidmar confirms squad for AFC Under 23s Championship |last=Smithies |first=Tom |date=23 December 2015 |work=Fox Sports}}</ref> where he played every minute of Australia's campaign in three games against the UAE, Vietnam and Jordan, scoring against Vietnam.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.the-afc.com/afcasfeeds?fixtureid=9816&stageid=385&tMode=C&view=ajax&show=matchsummary |title=Australia 0\u20131 United Arab Emirates |publisher=The Asian Football Confederation}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.the-afc.com/afcasfeeds?fixtureid=9817&stageid=385&tMode=C&view=ajax&show=matchsummary |title=Vietnam 0\u20132 Australia \u2013 Match Summary |publisher=The Asian Football Confederation}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.the-afc.com/afcasfeeds?fixtureid=9819&stageid=385&tMode=C&view=ajax&show=matchsummary |title=Jordan 0\u20130 Australia \u2013 Match Summary |publisher=The Asian Football Confederation}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Maclaren announced that he pledged to play for [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]], rather than play for Scotland.<ref>https://www.ftbl.com.au/news/maclaren-opens-up-about-cheeky-ffa-480939</ref> In May 2016, Maclaren was called up to the Socceroos for the first time for a friendly match away to [[England national football team|England]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.socceroos.com.au/article/fresh-faces-named-for-caltex-socceroos-england-clash/1lbdl3eall4g61v7uxqcn3ac86 |title=Fresh faces named for Caltex Socceroos' England clash |last=Greco |first=John |date=11 May 2016 |website=Socceroos.com.au |publisher=Football Federation Australia}}</ref> in which he started.<ref>{{cite news|title=England 2 \u2013 1 Australia|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36339159|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 May 2016|accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> After a solid start to the [[2016\u201317 A-League]] season, Maclaren was called up again to the Socceroos squad in November 2016 for Australia's [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Third Round|2018 World Cup Qualifying Third Round]] match against [[Thailand national football team|Thailand]] in Bangkok. He started the match, playing 57 minutes in the eventual 2\u20132 draw before being substituted for [[Nathan Burns]]. He was again called up for the final two Round 3 matches in August and September 2017, coming on in the 71st minute of the crucial final match at home to Thailand, which the Socceroos won 2\u20131.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-05/socceroos-v-thailand-world-cup-2018-qualifier-live-blog/8875104?section=sport Socceroos edge Thailand on frustrating night, as it happened], [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]], Dean Bilton, 5 September 2017</ref>\n\nMaclaren dropped out of the Australia squad later in 2017, due to his lack of playing time at Darmstadt. A major factor in him seeking a loan move in January 2018 was to try and earn selection for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]] squad.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44001217 |title=Jamie Maclaren: Striker eyes World Cup place & return to Hibernian |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 May 2018 |accessdate=7 May 2018}}</ref> He was named in a 32-man provisional squad for the World Cup,<ref>https://www.espn.co.uk/football/fifa-world-cup/story/3487741/australias-provisional-world-cup-squad-includes-tim-cahill-daniel-arzani</ref> but was cut from the 26-man squad to go to a pre-tournament camp in Turkey.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.socceroos.com.au/news/confirmed-van-marwijks-six-outs-caltex-socceroos-26-man-squad |title=Confirmed: Van Marwijk's six outs in Caltex Socceroos 26-man squad |work= |publisher=[[Football Federation Australia]] |date=15 May 2018}}</ref> Following an injury to [[Tomi Juric]], Maclaren was added to the training squad.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/maclaren-joins-up-with-socceroos-squad |title=Maclaren joins up with Socceroos squad |work=The World Game |publisher= |date=28 May 2018 |accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref> He played in a preparatory friendly match against [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44337258 |title=Australia 4\u20130 Czech Republic |publisher=BBC Sport |date=1 June 2018 |accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref> and was selected in the final 23-man squad.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jun/03/socceroos-world-cup-squad-jamie-maclaren-survives-the-cut |title=Socceroos World Cup squad: Jamie Maclaren survives the cut |work=The Guardian |publisher= |date=2 June 2018 |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIncoming Socceroo coach [[Graham Arnold]] selected Maclaren in the Australian squad for the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup]].<ref>[https://www.myfootball.com.au/news/caltex-socceroos-squad-afc-asian-cup-uae-2019tm-finalised Caltex Socceroos squad for AFC Asian Cup UAE 2019\u2122 finalised], Football Federation Australia, 20 December 2018</ref> He came on as a 64th minute substitute in the only pre-tournament friendly against [[Oman national football team|Oman]], and started all three matches in the group stage;  a loss against [[Jordan national football team|Jordan]], having a potential equaliser ruled offside, the second match against [[Palestine national football team|Palestine]], scoring his first international goal in the 18th minute with a header from a [[Tom Rogic]] cross, and the last game, a win against [[Syria national football team|Syria]]. Maclaren continued in the starting XI for the Socceroos in the first knockout stage match, against [[Uzbekistan national football team|Uzbekistan]], playing the first 75 minutes before being replaced by [[Apostolos Giannou]] in the eventual win on penalties. He was named to start alongside Giannou in a changed two-striker formation in the Quarter Final against hosts [[UAE national football team|UAE]].\n\nMaclaren scored a hat-trick in a 5&ndash;0 win against [[Nepal national football team|Nepal]] on 10 October 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/oct/10/jamie-maclaren-hits-hat-trick-as-socceroos-stroll-to-win-over-nepal |title=Jamie Maclaren hits hat-trick as Socceroos stroll to win over Nepal |newspaper=The Guardian |publisher= |date=10 October 2019 |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMaclaren holds a British passport, and is half-Maltese through his mother. This partial Maltese heritage led to [[Malta national football team|Malta]] approaching Maclaren to play for them, however, he turned down the request.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rugari|first1=Vince|title=A-League contract news: Jamie Maclaren on his Brisbane Roar future|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/news/aleague-contract-news-jamie-maclaren-on-his-brisbane-roar-future/news-story/14982817c815f27c939b15a4dded3811|website=Fox Sports Australia|publisher=News Corporation|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nMaclaren is a [[Aston Villa F.C.|Villa]] fan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Australia's new star Jamie MacLaren admits Aston Villa love, should Steve Bruce take interest?|url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2016/11/09/australias-new-star-jamie-maclaren-admits-aston-villa-love-shoul/|website=HITS Sports|publisher=News Corporation|accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|20 March 2020}}<ref>{{soccerway|299758|J. Maclaren|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League<sup>1</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continen